                           <seg type="script">Fine hand, characterized by the rounded script. Some letters appear more angular, especially the loop of the letter “ʿAin” at the forth order (ዓ “ʿA”). 
                              The space between the individual letters and the lines is broad.</seg>
                           <seg type="ink">Black; Vermilion.</seg>
                           <persName role="scribe" ref="PRS00000">Takla Krǝstos</persName>Takla Krǝstos is the scribe mentioned in the supplication formulas of Texts 1-2 in AKM-004α (e.g., in <locus target="3ra">3ra</locus> [ls.11-12], 6vb [ls. 6-7], 64rb [ls. 2-3]).&#xD;
                           <date notBefore="1800" notAfter="1900">19th century (?).</date>
                           <note>Some paleographical features:</note>
                           <note>In the text contained in <ref  target="#p1"/> the scribe uses to exchange the laryngeals. You can notice it for instance in the word ጸሓፊ᎓ “ṣaḥafi” (“scribe, copyst”), present often in the supplication formulas at the end of each miracle. Here it appears written also with the laryngeal “Ha” (ሀ) as in <locus target="14rb">14rb</locus> (l.1), and with the laryngeal “Ḫa” (ኀ), as in <locus target="64rb">64rb</locus> (l.2).</note>
                           <note>Other example of laryngeal exchanging is the verbal form የሀሉ written here የሐሉ (e.g., <locus target="6va">6va</locus> [l.18], 7vb [l.8]).</note>
                            <note>The punctuation used as sentence dividers generally is represented by the nine dot asterisk.</note>
                           
